    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "type": "ContextOfUse",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "High"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/rh-index-comparison-primary",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary relative hemolysis index validation against FDA pump experimental data",
      "description": "This is the principal validation result for the COU. The CFD model was exercised across all five flow-speed operating points (2.5 L/min at 2500 RPM, 3.5 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4.5 L/min at 3500 RPM, 5.0 L/min at 3800 RPM, and 6.0 L/min at 4200 RPM) using the Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model with constants C=3.62e-5, α=2.416, β=0.785. Experimental plasma-free hemoglobin measurements were collected from triplicate benchtop runs of the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry using bovine blood at 37 °C, haematocrit 35%. The normalised relative hemolysis index RH was computed as the ratio of model-predicted NIH to experimentally derived NIH. Across all five operating points the model yielded RH values of 0.81, 0.76, 0.89, 0.94, and 0.88, all satisfying the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. The mean absolute percentage error between predicted and measured NIH was 9.3%, within the 15% tolerance established for MRL 2. Mesh sensitivity was confirmed at 4.2 M cells with GCI < 2% on the hemolysis scalar. Turbulence closure used the SST k-ω model; wall y+ was maintained below 5 across all rotating surfaces. The analyst team reviewed all five operating-point comparisons in the validation review meeting of 2024-11-14 and confirmed acceptability. Full tabulated results are archived in the project data repository.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/fda-generic-pump-experimental-hemolysis"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/pressure-rise-verification",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pump pressure-rise characteristic validation",
      "description": "CFD-predicted pressure rise across the pump was compared against manufacturer-supplied pump curve data at three operating points. Agreement within 5% at all points confirmed adequate bulk flow fidelity prior to hemolysis scalar transport.",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/morrison/data/pump-geometry-tolerance-sweep",
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/morrison/activity/pressure-curve-validation-run-2024-10"
    },
    {
